        "text": "Luke 6:38",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"into your bosom\"). The thing to be repaid follows in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 65:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; it is not governed, however, by shillamtı̄, as the form of the address clearly shows, but by 'ăshallēm understood, which may easily be supplied. Whether 'ăsher is to be taken in the sense of qui or quod (that), it is hardly possible to decide; but the construction of the sentence favours the latter. Sacrificing \"upon mountains and hills\" (and, what is omitted, here, \"under every green tree\") is the well-known standing phrase used to describe the idolatry of the times preceding the captivity (cf., ",
